Spec ad for the new fragrance Revasser. Fragrance ads are an interesting one, they’re never selling you a product, however they sell a feeling, mood, or a lifestyle. Our ad here shows our aggravating it can be living in the public eye, constantly scrutinized, observed and judged, and everywhere you look there’s another “camera”. Keeping it more cinematic with the flares and the vague narrative allows you to feel something, rather than be sold something. This commercial was lit with the @westcottlighting L60-B using their in lighting effects to create the flashes, and filmed on the @fujifilmx_us xh2s with my @tamronamericas 35/1.8. Hello, figured I haven’t done a proper intro in quite a while so what better time than now. I’m the son of a painter and mechanic, that influence is likely what led me to a career in photography. Before that I pursued a career in optometry (clearly wasn’t for me). Photography was the thing that I truly felt gave my life purpose, and myself, an identity. At my current age of 39 I can honestly say I’ve lived several lives. In addition to optometry I was playing high level competitive golf too. In high school I was a drummer in a ska band called “the pickup sticks”. I’ve built several motorcycles and found a love of machines about 10 years ago (my dad’s influence). However of all of the things I’ve done, nothing has ever made me feel as good or confidant as photography has. In 2019 I nearly lost everything in a terrible motorcycle accident that left me nearly immobile and even dead for a few mins. Life is a wild ride, but having a partner in photography, keeps the car on the road. If you’re a new follower, welcome, if you’ve been here before, thank you. A different kind of post. What you see, is some gross old shoes. What I see? Stories. Connection is an interesting thing. I’ve had these shoes for well over 12-15 years. They’re covered in oil, gasoline, paint, dirt, and even some blood. They’ve seen most of the country. I was wearing these when I rode my first motorcycle. Also when I built my first.  Anytime I’ve run out to my garage to work on something I’d put these on. When doing photoshoots I would always throw these on because they felt familiar, comfortable, and when my anxiety would be killing me and my nerves were out of control on a big shoot, I’d look down at these beat up shoes and remind myself that everything is ok. If these shoes can make it, so can I.  Paint is on them are from when I’ve painted backdrops for shoots in my driveway. Hell, even through med school and moving out into my first new house, I had these. They’ve been with me through so much, and anytime I’m throwing things out, I always stop myself before they go one the trash. Shoes are so interesting. They never show where you’re going, just where you’ve been. And I’m proud of how far I’ve come. I don’t wear these anymore, but when I look at them I just kinda smile. #withmytamron #withmytamronmirrorless #withmytamronprime #tamron3514 #tamron2470 #tamron4518 #tamron8518 #tamron2470 #westcottlighting #westcott #fj400 #fj200 #fuji #fujigfx100 #fujixh2s #mediumformat #wonderfulmachine #mrepresents #portrait #editorial #commercialphotography #jthorpephoto #apa #apadc @photopolitic @phillyreps @apa_dc @mrepresents #shoes #history

So excited to share this piece I directed and shot for @thewashingtonballet in partnership with @citycenterdc . For this shoot, I wanted the feel to be a little more chaotic with an organic handheld motion, so the decision to not use a tradition gimbal was made. Another decision I made was to film at night. The main purpose of the video was to advertise the ballet performances they do outside in the plaza, so having it have a similar feel was also important. Finally the last creative decision was to have the dancers perform on the skim with water flowing constantly over it. This last piece is what makes the video. It shows the movement in such a beautiful way, that combined with the jerkyness of the camera, makes for a dynamic, beautiful piece.

An evening with @adamconover Such a fun night shooting with Adam. My camera often does take me to some of the most interesting places. Last night shooting drag performers at Shakers in DC. I knew I didn’t want to do my “normal” lighting for these. They needed to feel raw, with lots of energy, and to feel in the moment. So that meant wide angle lens and flash on camera. It really took me back to my old days of shooting street work, something a lot of you guys don’t know got me started in shooting portrait work. It was such a fun night of dancing, music, and just overall insanity haha, and being able to just shoot meant I could pay attention to the story details the photos needed. SNL vibes with @mrtommymcfly ! Shot these in studio a couple weeks ago with Tommy, and really wanted our shoot to feel entertainment driven, given his career on tv. Working with on air talent is a blast! You get to photograph their personality vs just a headshot of something, so I wanted an editorial/interesting look to these. We did that by coloring our shadows, by using two @westcottlighting fj200’s gelled with complimenting colors mounted directly next to each other, they combine to make a white light on him, however when that light casts a shadow behind, we see our two colors revealed. Pretty neat trick! Shot on my @fujifilmx_us gfx100s using my @tamronamericas 45/1.8.

The Cottontail Killer
My 2023 Halloween shoot is in the books! For this years shoot we created our own slasher character affectionately named “Cottontail” very loosely inspired by the bunnyman bridge folk lore. We actually pulled this shoot together very quickly, as I had said I was done doing these Halloween shoots, but every year something pulls me back in! For the photo, our key light was a @westcottlighting #FJ400 through a medium switch octa, then through a 4x4 scrim. Camera left was a #fj200 with a switch BD for rim. Camera right was a barebulb FJ200 to help fill the room. Photo was shot on the @fujifilmx_us gfx100s and the @tamronamericas 45/1.8.

One of the most amazing things about having a career like mine, is the opportunity to meet all different kinds of people. Enter Rev. Dr. Sandra Elena Canchita Butler-Truesdale. I met Sandra while working on projects for @noraleeus and I knew immediately just how special of a woman she was. Her life story would far exceed IG’s caption, but please just know she was and is a massive influence in Washington DC especially the African American music scene early on. On shoots we’d often joke with each other, and I’d purposefully misname the old artists she used to work with to make her laugh. I’d say “tell me how it was to work with Martin Gaye?” (Instead of Marvin) and she’d laugh and say “boy you need help” Everytime we crossed paths we’d make the same jokes. She was always postive and a joy to be around.
Sandra passed away sadly on October 28th, and while I’ll always miss her and her sass, I’m so happy and lucky to have shot some beautiful portraits of her throughout the years, with this being my favorite one. Thank you to @brandtricca for introducing us as I know she thought the world of you.
